Itis remarkable, however, how many difficulties the last thirty pages of the Dialogus present compared with the smoothness of what has gone before. We have first one chapter which only exists in a single manu- script 3 then another which is only given by four out of nine, and the place of which in these four is quite unex- plainable3 then a total abandonment of the Dialogue form3 lastly, an Epilogus which is not, as it professes to be, merely a summary of the preceding arguments, but a fresh treatment of the subject, though on similar lines Is it possible that there were two editions of the Dialogus, of which the first may be represented by the Vienna MSS. which have no Appendixâ€š while the second con- tained new chapters not very artistically dovetailed into
